english:
  title: Second Memorial Requesting the Suspension of the Capital Relocation
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant possesses no merit, yet undeservedly receives Your Majesty's grace. I have been permitted to join the ranks of the meritorious and married into the royal house. My father and I alike have gained honor, and my station has been elevated high. Though I were ground to dust, I could never repay such kindness. My only wish, however humble, is to contribute even the smallest fraction to the virtue of Your Majesty—this thought dwells in my heart day and night.

    Yet fortune reversed itself. My merit was slight, my rank excessive. The excess of blessing bred calamity. Last winter I fell gravely ill, recovering only after a month. In the first month of this year, an abscess erupted upon my back, then again in the fifth month, and once more in the seventh. Each time it strikes, it lingers for ten days before subsiding. My hearing has always been poor, and since the seventh month my eyes have dimmed most severely. After sunset, I perceive nothing at all. The condition worsens daily; I fear I approach blindness. My vital force grows weak, my spirit clouded, my memory scattered. On the eighth of this month, I was seized by vertigo, fell to the ground, and nearly departed this life. Only through Your Majesty's grace—the medicines granted, the physicians summoned, the careful ministrations—did I recover. Yet to this very day, I remain unwell.

    I measure my decline and think: how much longer can such a decrepit vessel remain in this world? I fear that soon I shall bid farewell to this prosperous age, dying before I might serve with loyalty, bearing forever the debt of Your Majesty's grace. This is my deepest dread.

    Therefore, I recently took up my brush despite my illness and submitted a memorial, risking the displeasure of heaven itself. I cited the year's famine and humbly requested that the relocation of the capital be postponed. Your Majesty's benevolence is vast and generous—you did not reproach me but offered kind words of explanation. You have already informed the ancestral shrine and the Dowager; the decision is fixed. What I said cannot sway you.

    Yet upon receiving this imperial word, my gratitude deepens and my simple heart is stirred. I perceive that Your Highness honors deeply both the service to the ancestral shrine and the care of the Dowager, your filial piety most sincere. But surely the spirits of the shrine and the Dowager's heart alike must regard the relief of the people and the preservation of the realm as paramount. If you report the people's hunger to the shrine and beseech future harvests, if you report it to the Dowager and await better times—would not the shrine listen? Would not the Dowager consent? Then Your Highness's filial devotion would be fulfilled, and your virtue of cherishing the people would shine ever brighter.

    But if you show no compassion for the people's hunger, if you hastily proceed with relocation and thereby afflict them and endanger the foundation of the state—how could this accord with the Way of preservation and stewardship? How could this fulfill the duty to continue your ancestors' will and complete their works?

    In ancient times, King Wu wished to establish his capital at Luoyang. The Duke of Zhou and the Duke of Zhao undertook its construction and established the ancestral shrine. Yet King Cheng, after making offerings there, returned to the ancestral capital at Zhouxian and never moved again. This was because his time knew neither the Yellow River's fury that Pang Geng faced nor the invasions of the Di people that King Tai endured. The people lived in peace upon their lands, so relocation was unnecessary. Later generations never faulted King Cheng for this. Indeed, when ancient kings relocated their capitals, it was always for the people's benefit. Now, when relocation brings no such benefit yet you wish it desperately—is this not ill-advised? Though Your Highness remain here and never move, this would accord with King Cheng's precedent and later ages would not blame you. Moreover, if you await better times, surely a fitting occasion for relocation will come. Why then rush so urgently this very year?

    Your Highness has studied the ancients. You have seen that rulers who ignored the people's hunger and allowed them to freeze and starve are remembered as lacking humanity. I fear posterity may apply this same judgment to what we do today.

    Moreover, famine always breeds banditry. When the people's efforts are divided between two capitals, the young and strong depart while the old and weak remain behind—bandits will surely flourish. Should ruthless gangs gather to pillage and, fearing punishment, plot rebellion, how fearful that would be! Of late, when common folk hear of the relocation, many weep and seem to have lost will to live. When hunger and cold pierce the body, few resist the temptation to theft. The realm's greatest troubles arise from what is neglected—this danger too cannot be ignored.

    If Your Highness believes the decision already fixed and therefore cannot hastily alter it, then I beseech you: share this memorial with your ministers and with the common people. Consult them on whether the decision can be changed. Then let whatever determination emerges be acted upon. Whether it changes or not, it will reflect the realm's true consensus, not Your Highness's alone judgment. Even if the decision changes, what could be wrong with that? The realm is a sacred trust. You must hold it in a place of safety together with all the people, not place it alone in danger and show them no compassion.

    Your people hunger and shiver below, harboring resentment, while above you alone guard the sacred trust. This is like placing a weight of ten thousand jun upon eggs stacked upon one another—collapse and catastrophe are inevitable. I truly fear this. My heart truly grieves.

    Though I have received unparalleled grace and find no way to repay it, if there is anything to be said, how could I dare withhold my words for fear of blame and thus betray Your Majesty's enlightenment? I submit this to your sacred consideration. My gratitude would be boundless. Your servant is thoroughly presumptuous and inadequate.
